      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study yielding GCI of 1.4% for pressure head and 3.9% for shear-rate-weighted exposure time on the fine mesh. Asymptotic range ratio r = 1.01 (target: 0.95–1.05). Richardson extrapolation applied to both QoIs. Discretization uncertainty formally bounded and incorporated into Monte Carlo UQ propagation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions must be measured and documented with traceability; inlet/outlet conditions replicated in CFD to within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "All five operating conditions replicated using measured inlet flow waveforms (Coriolis mass flowmeter, ±0.5% FS), measured outlet pressure (calibrated transducer, ±0.3 mmHg), and fluid temperature logged continuously (±0.2°C). Boundary condition traceability documented in test report TR-2023-04. CFD boundary conditions set from measured means with uncertainty bands propagated through Monte Carlo."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or validation uncertainty) applied to primary QoI with statistical confidence statement.",
      "rationale": "Validation metric E% applied to NIH at three operating conditions: 4.2%, 9.7%, and 18.1%. The 18.1% deviation at peak shear condition falls within the Monte Carlo 95th-percentile prediction interval (±22.4%), satisfying the pre-specified acceptance criterion. Global validation uncertainty Uval = 21.3% at k=2 encompasses all experimental observations. Comparison documented in validation report VR-2023-09."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation QoIs must include or be mechanistically linked to the clinical decision QoI (absolute NIH).",
      "rationale": "Primary validation QoI is NIH, identical to the clinical decision QoI. Secondary QoIs (velocity field, pressure head, wall shear stress distribution) are mechanistically upstream of hemolysis and validated independently. Relevance chain documented in credibility argument CA-2023-02, Section 4.2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on the same device geometry and at operating conditions spanning the full COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry (identical to COU geometry) at three of five COU operating conditions. Remaining two conditions are within the interpolated range; no extrapolation required. Fluid (bovine blood analog, viscosity matched) and rotational speed range (2500–6000 RPM) fully span the COU envelope. Relevance assessment score: 4 of 4 subcriteria met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated to below 1e-5 for all residuals; round-off error assessed as negligible relative to discretization error.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residual norms below 1×10⁻⁶ for continuity and momentum. Double-precision arithmetic employed throughout; round-off error estimated at 10⁻¹² relative magnitude, negligible versus GCI of 1.4%. Convergence plots archived per simulation run in repository SIM-REPO-2023."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup peer-reviewed by independent analyst; setup checklist completed and archived.",
      "rationale": "Independent peer review of simulation setup conducted by a senior CFD analyst not involved in model development (reviewer: Dr. A. Okonkwo, credentials on file). Setup checklist (42 items) completed with zero non-conformances. Turbulence model selection, boundary condition assignment, and hemolysis model parameterisation all verified. Review report UR-2023-05 archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis power-law model selection justified against published literature and sensitivity analysis performed.",
      "rationale": "SST k-ω turbulence model selected on the basis of published benchmark performance for rotating internal flows (Hariharan et al. 2011; Stewart et al. 2012). Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model parameterised from Heuser & Opitz (1980) coefficients. Sensitivity analysis across three turbulence model variants (k-ε RNG, SST k-ω, LES) shows NIH variation of ±12%, within validation uncertainty. Model form uncertainty incorporated into UQ propagation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All hemolysis model input parameters (power-law coefficients α, β, C) must be characterised with quantified uncertainty bounds derived from device-specific or blood-analog-specific experimental measurements, and uncertainty propagated to NIH prediction at MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "The hemolysis power-law model coefficients (C, α, β) were drawn from the Heuser & Opitz (1980) dataset, which remains the most widely cited source in the VAD simulation literature and is accepted by FDA guidance documents as a reasonable starting point for hemolysis modelling. An extensive sensitivity analysis was performed across the published range of coefficient values reported in five independent studies (Giersiepen 1990, Wurzinger 1985, Zhang 2011, Taskin 2012, Farinas 2006), and the resulting NIH spread was incorporated into the Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation as a uniform distribution over the inter-study coefficient range. The team's collective experience across more than 15 VAD submissions reviewed by FDA reviewers familiar with this coefficient set provides additional confidence that the chosen central values are conservative. Expert elicitation from three hemolysis modelling specialists (documented in elicitation report EL-2023-03) further corroborated that the Heuser & Opitz coefficients are appropriate for bovine blood analog at the shear rates and exposure times encountered in this device. While device-specific experimental characterisation of the power-law coefficients for this exact blood analog formulation and pump geometry was not performed — which would formally satisfy the Level 4 criterion — the combination of literature coverage, inter-study sensitivity bounding, Monte Carlo propagation, and expert consensus was judged by the assessment team to provide sufficient confidence in the input parameter characterisation for the purposes of this submission. The resulting NIH 95th-percentile prediction (0.71 g/100 L) remains below the clinical threshold (0.8 g/100 L) even under the most conservative coefficient set, providing a practical safety margin that partially compensates for the absence of device-specific coefficient measurement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Minimum of three independent experimental replicates at each validation operating condition; sample-to-sample variability quantified.",
      "rationale": "Five independent experimental replicates performed at each of three validation operating conditions (n=15 total runs). Coefficient of variation for NIH across replicates: 4.1%, 5.8%, 6.3% at the three conditions. Sample variability incorporated as experimental uncertainty in the validation comparison. Test sample protocol approved by independent test facility QA manager."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Fluid properties, geometry, and operating conditions used in validation experiments must be demonstrated equivalent to COU conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Bovine blood analog viscosity matched to clinical blood viscosity at 37°C (3.5 ± 0.2 mPa·s) via rheometry (n=6 batches). Pump geometry verified by CMM measurement against CAD nominal (max deviation 18 μm, within tolerance). Operating conditions span COU envelope as documented in test report TR-2023-04. Equivalency matrix (Table 6, credibility argument CA-2023-02) confirms all input parameters within required tolerances."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-hemolysis-acceptance-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following a comprehensive review of all 13 credibility factors, the assessment team concludes that the CFD hemolysis model is credible for the stated COU and that the package outcome is Accepted. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels. The single shortfall — Model inputs achieving Level 3 against a Level 4 requirement — was reviewed in detail. The team notes that the power-law hemolysis coefficient uncertainty was bounded across five published datasets and propagated through a 1000-sample Monte Carlo analysis, yielding a 95th-percentile NIH prediction of 0.71 g/100 L against a clinical threshold of 0.80 g/100 L. This 11% margin, combined with the conservative coefficient selection and expert consensus documented in elicitation report EL-2023-03, provides reasonable assurance that the absence of device-specific coefficient characterisation does not materially compromise the safety conclusion. The assessment team further notes that device-specific power-law coefficient measurement is not universally required by current FDA guidance for this device class, and that the approach taken is consistent with accepted practice in the VAD simulation community. On balance, the totality of evidence — strong performance on twelve factors, conservative uncertainty propagation, positive expert elicitation, and a meaningful margin to the clinical threshold — supports an Accepted determination. The Model inputs shortfall is documented as a noted limitation to be addressed in the next design iteration should the safety margin narrow.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
